04130nam a22006735i 9780231536028DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20132013nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2013016275  a(OCoLC)862939715  a97802315360287 a10.7312/kahn164382doi  a(DE-B1597)458983  a(OCoLC)862325850  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aPN1995b.K255 2013 7aPHI0050002bisacsh1 aKahn, Paul, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFinding Ourselves at the Movies :bPhilosophy for a New Generation /cPaul Kahn. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (256 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tPart I. From Philosophy to Film -- tIntroduction -- t1. Philosophy, Democracy, and the Turn to Film -- t2. Freedom and Persuasion -- t3. On Interpretation -- tPart II. film and the social imaginary -- tIntroduction -- t4. Violence and the State -- t5. Love, Romance, and Pornography -- tConclusion: Film, Faith, and Love -- tNotes -- tBibliography: Essays on Sources -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAcademic philosophy may have lost its audience, but the traditional subjects of philosophy—love, death, justice, knowledge, and faith—remain as compelling as ever. To reach a new generation, Paul W. Kahn argues that philosophy must take up these fundamental concerns as we find them in contemporary culture. He demonstrates how this can be achieved through a turn to popular film.Discussing such well-known movies as Forrest Gump (1994), The American President (1995), The Matrix (1999), Memento (2000), The History of Violence (2005), Gran Torino (2008), The Dark Knight (2008), The Road (2009), and Avatar (2009), Kahn explores powerful archetypes and their hold on us. His inquiry proceeds in two parts. First, he uses film to explore the nature of action and interpretation, arguing that narrative is the critical concept for understanding both. Second, he explores the narratives of politics, family, and faith as they appear in popular films. Engaging with genres as diverse as romantic comedy, slasher film, and pornography, Kahn explores the social imaginary through which we create and maintain a meaningful world. He finds in popular films a new setting for a philosophical inquiry into the timeless themes of sacrifice, innocence, rebirth, law, and love.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aMotion pictures - Philosophy. 0aMotion picturesxPhilosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Ethics & Moral Philosophy.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044247240uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/kahn1643840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231536028423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231536028/original  a978-3-11-044247-2  Columbia University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK